{"ts":"2026-06-27T10:53:22.691Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_end","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Identifying API Routes**\n\nI've initially identified a limited set of existing API routes: `/health`, `/logs`, and `/auth`. However, the current focus shifts to model schema creation, specifically Pydantic schemas for the MVP backend models. I am disregarding the landing page and GFF AI tool components as per the explicit requirements. I'm prioritizing creation, update, and list/read response schemas for the User model, where appropriate.\n\n\n**Refining Data Schemas**\n\nI'm now focusing on the data schemas, specifically for ClientAccount, Project, and AgentOperation, as well as DocumentItem, Invoice, SupportTicket, and GovernanceItem. I've also added the required auth schemas like LoginRequest and CurrentUserResponse, keeping them straightforward. My strategy is to use `from_attributes` or ORM mode as appropriate, and I'm ensuring hashed passwords are not exposed. I'm also ensuring the response fields align with frontend needs. I need to conduct backend import checks after these updates, and examine the structure of `backend/app/schemas/user.py` to keep that in mind when making edits.\n\n\n**Structuring Schema Files**\n\nI'm now focusing on file organization for the schemas. I've decided to consolidate `UserBase`, `UserCreate`, `UserUpdate`, `UserResponse`, and `UserList` (or a `UserListResponse`) within `backend/app/schemas/user.py`. I'm including a `CurrentUserResponse`, carefully considering its required fields: id, name, full_name, email, role, status, is_active, created_at, updated_at, and client_id. I've also double-checked the existing user model to ensure I have all the relevant fields such as the id, name, and full_name.\n\n\n**Reviewing Response Schemas**\n\nI'm checking the `UserResponse` schema now, ensuring the `hashed_password` field is omitted from the response. I've been reviewing the database model for `ClientAccount`, specifically its `id`, `name`, and `industry` fields, and the existing `backend/app/schemas/client_account.py` to ensure alignment with the database model. I'll need to consider this in constructing the relevant schema.\n\n\n**Defining ClientAccount Schemas**\n\nI'm now implementing the ClientAccount schemas. I've defined `ClientAccountBase`, `ClientAccountCreate`, `ClientAccountUpdate` (with all fields optional), and `ClientAccountResponse`. I'm including `id` and `created_at` in the response model. All these will be placed in `backend/app/schemas/client_account.py`. I'm next moving on to defining the Project schemas and reviewing associated database fields.\n\n\n**Constructing Project Schemas**\n\nI'm now creating the Project schemas. I'm defining `ProjectBase`, `ProjectCreate`, `ProjectUpdate` (with all fields optional), and `ProjectResponse`. The response model will include `id`, `client_id`, `name`, `phase`, `status`, `health`, `owner`, `start_date`, `target_date`, `progress`, and `description`. These are now being placed in `backend/app/schemas/project.py`. I'm next looking at the AgentOperation model.\n\n\n**Defining AgentOperation Schemas**\n\nI'm now implementing the `AgentOperation` schemas, including `AgentOperationBase`, `AgentOperationCreate`, `AgentOperationUpdate` (with optional fields), and `AgentOperationResponse`. The `AgentOperationResponse` will include `id` and `last_activity_at`. These schemas are now organized in `backend/app/schemas/agent_operation.py`. Now I will move to the `DocumentItem` model.\n\n\n\n**Defining Document Schemas**\n\nI'm now creating schemas for `DocumentItem`, including `DocumentItemBase`, `DocumentItemCreate`, `DocumentItemUpdate` (with optional fields), and `DocumentItemResponse` containing `id` and `created_at`. These are being placed in `backend/app/schemas/document_item.py`. I'm next starting to define the schemas for the `Invoice` model.\n\n**Defining Invoice Schemas**\n\nI'm now defining schemas for the `Invoice` model. I've created `InvoiceBase` and `InvoiceCreate` schemas, which are critical for processing invoices in the backend. I'm focusing on the fields `invoice_number`, `status`, `amount`, and `due_date`, and I'm mindful of the relationships with `client_id` and `project_id`. The remaining schemas will follow.\n\n\n**Defining Invoice/Ticket Schemas**\n\nI've added the `InvoiceUpdate` and `InvoiceResponse` schemas, placing them in `backend/app/schemas/invoice.py`. Now, I'm defining `SupportTicketBase`, `SupportTicketCreate`, and a fully optional `SupportTicketUpdate` schema. I'm focusing on the fields from the database model, including relationships, for a comprehensive implementation.\n\n\n**Finalizing Core Schemas**\n\nI've just defined the `SupportTicketResponse` schema, including `id` and `created_at`, placing it within `backend/app/schemas/support_ticket.py`. I've also implemented the schemas for `GovernanceItem`, including base, create, update (with all fields optional), and response models featuring the `id`. These are now located in `backend/app/schemas/governance_item.py`. I'm now adding auth schemas like `LoginRequest` and `TokenResponse`.\n\n\n**Structuring Auth Schemas**\n\nI'm now structuring the authentication schemas. I've decided to create `LoginRequest`, `TokenResponse`, and `CurrentUserResponse`. I'm going to create a dedicated `backend/app/schemas/auth.py` file to keep things clean. I'll include `username` and `password`, or `email` and `password` inside `LoginRequest`.\n\n\n"}}
